<DOC><DOCNO> AP890915-0175 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-09-15-89 1848EDT</FILEID><FIRST>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     09-15 0293</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0299</SECOND><HEAD>Rain Along West Coast; Thunderstorms in Nation's Midsection</HEAD><BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE><TEXT>   Showers and thunderstorms reached across the Midwest and parts ofthe South on Friday, and forecasters predicted the first rain inmonths for Los Angeles on Saturday.   Showers were reported in West Virginia, Kentucky, southernIndiana and Illionois, eastern and southern Kentucky, western NorthCarolina and from southeast Louisiana across the Florida panhandle.   Nashville had .67 inches of rain during a six-hour period endingat 2 p.m. EDT.   A rain advisory was posted Saturday over the central San JoaquinValley in California. Forecasters said there was a good chance forlight rain Saturday over Los Angeles _ which would be its first rainsince May.   Northern Nevada also had a good chance for rain during theweekend, with snow possible in the eastern Sierra Nevada by Monday.   The nation's low temperature Friday was 21 degrees at Gunnison,Colo. Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 53degrees at Arcata, Calif., to 101 degrees at Gila Bend, Ariz.   Saturday's forecast called for showers and thunderstorms fromsouthern New England and much of New York state, across Georgia andnorthern Florida, the Ohio and Tennessee valleys; scattered rainfrom the lower two-thirds of the California coast into Nevada;warmer weather over the mid-Mississippi Valley and central Plainsbut cooler over much of the Pacific states.   High temperatures were expected to be in the 60s and 70s from NewEngland across Maryland, from the Great Lakes through the TennesseeValley over the middle Mississippi Valley, southern Rockies, PacificNorthwest, along the California coast; near 90 degrees over theFlorida peninsula; in the 90s in the desert Southwest; and in the80s over the remainder of the nation.</TEXT></DOC>